[severity:It bothers me. A fix would be nice]
Suppose you have this code:

```csharp
public interface IInterface
{
    string? Name { get; }
}
public abstract class Class1
    : IInterface
{
    public string[] Name { get; }

public Class1(
        string[] name)
    {
        Name = name;
    }
}
```

The line with `: IInterface` shows this error:

* `error CS0738: 'Class1' does not implement interface member 'IInterface.Name'. 'Class1.Name' cannot implement 'IInterface.Name' because it does not have the matching return type of 'string'`

The Quick Actions (codefixes) on that line include the option “Implement interface abstractly”:

! [Implement interface abstractly] (https://i.imgur.com/LYeVj2M.png)

However, when I run that Quick Action (codefix), I get the following result:

```csharp
public interface IInterface
{
    string? Name { get; }
}
public abstract class Class1
    : IInterface
{
    public string[] Name { get; }
    string? IInterface.Name { get; }

public Class1(
        string[] name)
    {
        Name = name;
    }
}
```

That is, the interface is implemented concretely as the added property is an auto-implemented property instead of an abstract property. Instead, I would expect code like the following to be generated.

```csharp
public interface IInterface
{
    string? Name { get; }
}
public abstract class Class1
    : IInterface
{
    public string[] Name { get; }
    string? IInterface.Name => Name1;
    protected abstract string? Name1 { get; }

public Class1(
        string[] name)
    {
        Name = name;
    }
}
```

I expect this code because the strategy of creating new properties with numbers when conflicts are encountered is used by Quick Actions like “Replace 'GetName' with property”:

! [“Replace 'GetName' with property” Quick Action] (https://i.imgur.com/B6NbIiC.png)

